 {"id":"rust_proxy-o4n","title":"Feature: Enhanced network diagnostic commands","description":"## Overview

Add diagnostic commands to help users troubleshoot proxy connectivity and configuration issues.

## Strategic Value (Score: 8/10)

Network issues are notoriously hard to debug. Diagnostic commands:
- Reduce support burden by enabling self-service troubleshooting
- Build user confidence in the tool
- Surface issues that would otherwise require deep investigation
- Make the tool feel professional and complete

## Commands

### `rp doctor`
Comprehensive health check of the entire setup:
```
$ rp doctor
Checking configuration... OK
Checking proxy connectivity...
  proxy-a: OK (latency: 45ms)
  proxy-b: FAIL (connection refused)
Checking DNS resolution... OK
Checking listen port... OK (127.0.0.1:8080 available)
Checking state directory... OK (writable)

Summary: 1 issue found
  - proxy-b: Connection refused to 192.168.1.100:3128
```

### `rp ping [proxy-id]`
Test connectivity and measure latency:
```
$ rp ping proxy-a
PING proxy-a (192.168.1.50:3128)
Response 1: time=42ms
Response 2: time=45ms
Response 3: time=43ms
--- proxy-a statistics ---
3 requests, 3 responses, 0% loss
min/avg/max = 42/43.3/45 ms
```

### `rp trace <target>`
Trace a connection through the proxy:
```
$ rp trace https://api.example.com
Resolving api.example.com... 93.184.216.34
Selecting proxy... proxy-a (round_robin)
Connecting to proxy... OK (32ms)
Sending CONNECT request... OK
Proxy response: HTTP/1.1 200 Connection Established
TLS handshake... OK (TLS 1.3)
Connection established in 156ms total
```

## Implementation Plan

1. Add doctor command with comprehensive checks
2. Add ping command for proxy latency testing
3. Add trace command for connection debugging
4. Integrate diagnostics into check command

## Acceptance Criteria

- doctor command checks config, connectivity, DNS, ports
- ping command measures proxy latency
- trace command shows full connection flow
- Clear, actionable output for failures
